05371nam a22007815i 9780812201277DE-B159720220424125308.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220424t20132003pau    fo  d z      eng d  a97808122012777 a10.9783/97808122012772doi  a(DE-B1597)448982  a(OCoLC)979741099  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 7aREL0400302bisacsh1 aBiddick, Kathleen, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Typological Imaginary :bCircumcision, Technology, History /cKathleen Biddick. 1aPhiladelphia : bUniversity of Pennsylvania Press, c[2013] 4c©2003  a1 online resource (160 p.) :b16 illus.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIllustrations -- tIntroduction: Typology Never Lets Go -- tChapter 1. Christians Mapping Jews: Cartography, Temporality, and the Typological Imaginary -- tChapter 2. Printing Excision: The Graphic Afterlife of Medieval Universal Histories -- tChapter 3. Graphic Reoccupation, the Faithful Synagogue, and Foucault’s Genealogy -- tChapter 4. Lachrymose History, the Typological Imaginary, and the Lacanian Enlightenment -- tChapter 5. Translating the Foreskin -- tNotes -- tIndex -- tAcknowledgments0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn this book Kathleen Biddick investigates the fate of the enduring timelines fabricated by early Christians to distinguish themselves from their Jewish neighbors. Ranging widely across the history of text, technology, and book art, she relates three interwoven stories: the Christians' translation of circumcision into a graphic problem of writing on the heart; the temporal construction of Christian notions of history based on the binary supersession of an Old Testament past by the present of a new dispensation; and the traumatic repetition of the graphic cutting off of Christians from Jews in academic history and anthropology.Moving beyond well-studied theological polemics, Biddick works from the relatively unfamiliar vantage point of the graphic technologies used in medieval and early modern texts and print sources, from maps to trial transcripts to universal histories. Addressing current concerns about the posthuman condition by linking them to a deeper genealogy of disembodiment at the technological heart of imaginary fantasies, she argues that such supersessionary practices extend to contemporary psychoanalytic and postcolonial texts, even as they propose alternative ways of thinking about memory and temporality. Crucial to Biddick's study is the ethical challenge of unbinding the typological imaginary, not in order to disavow theological difference but rather to open up the encounter between Christian and Jew to less deadening teleological readings.Making a significant contribution to the large debate over the transition from "scriptural" to "scientific" culture in Europe, The Typological Imaginary also succeeds in shedding light on the centrality of Jews to medieval and Enlightenment history.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aChristianity and other religionsxJudaism. 0aJudaism (Christian theology)xHistory of doctrinesyMiddle Ages, 600-1500. 0aJudaismxRelationsxChristianity. 0aTypology (Theology)xHistory of doctrinesyMiddle Ages, 600-1500. 4aLiterature. 7aRELIGION / Judaism / History.2bisacsh  aCultural Studies.  aHistory.  aLiterature.  aMedieval and Renaissance Studies.  aReligion.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn Press eBook Package Complete Collectionz978311041345808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn Press eBook Package Religionz978311041358808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Pennsylvania Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311045954840uhttps://d